# 🚀 Arduino IDE Cheat Sheet

### 📚 Most Common Arduino Commands Explained

> 💡 **Quick Reference Guide** for beginners and intermediate Arduino developers.

---

# 🏗️ 1. Basic Program Structure

## ⚙️ `setup()`

Runs **only once** when the board powers on or resets.

```cpp
void setup() {
  pinMode(13, OUTPUT);
}
```

### 🎯 Purpose

✅ Configure pins

✅ Initialize sensors/modules

✅ Start serial communication

---

## 🔄 `loop()`

Runs continuously after `setup()` completes.

```cpp
void loop() {
  digitalWrite(13, HIGH);
}
```

### 🎯 Purpose

✅ Read sensors

✅ Control actuators

✅ Execute repetitive tasks

---

# 🔌 2. Pin Control Commands

## 🟢 `pinMode()`

Sets a pin as INPUT or OUTPUT.

```cpp
pinMode(13, OUTPUT);
```

| Mode            | Description               |
| --------------- | ------------------------- |
| 🟢 OUTPUT       | Output mode               |
| 🔵 INPUT        | Input mode                |
| 🟡 INPUT_PULLUP | Internal pull-up resistor |

---

## 💡 `digitalWrite()`

Writes a digital value to a pin.

```cpp
digitalWrite(13, HIGH);
```

| Value   | Meaning |
| ------- | ------- |
| 🟢 HIGH | Logic 1 |
| 🔴 LOW  | Logic 0 |

---

## 📥 `digitalRead()`

Reads the state of a digital pin.

```cpp
int state = digitalRead(2);
```

Returns:

```cpp
HIGH
LOW
```

---

## 🎚️ `analogRead()`

Reads an analog signal.

```cpp
int value = analogRead(A0);
```

### 📊 Range

```text
0 → 1023
```

---

## 🎛️ `analogWrite()`

Outputs a PWM signal.

```cpp
analogWrite(9, 128);
```

### 📊 Range

```text
0 → 255
```

---

# ⏱️ 3. Timing Functions

## ⌛ `delay()`

Pauses program execution.

```cpp
delay(1000);
```

### Example

```cpp
delay(1000); // 1 second
```

⚠️ Blocks the processor while waiting.

---

## 🕒 `millis()`

Returns elapsed milliseconds since startup.

```cpp
unsigned long currentTime = millis();
```

### Common Uses

✅ Non-blocking timing

✅ Task scheduling

✅ Timers

---

## ⚡ `micros()`

Returns elapsed microseconds.

```cpp
unsigned long time = micros();
```

---

# 📡 4. Serial Communication

## 🚀 `Serial.begin()`

Starts serial communication.

```cpp
Serial.begin(9600);
```

### Common Baud Rates

| Speed  |
| ------ |
| 9600   |
| 57600  |
| 115200 |

---

## 📝 `Serial.print()`

Prints data without a new line.

```cpp
Serial.print("Hello");
```

Output:

```text
HelloWorld
```

---

## 📄 `Serial.println()`

Prints data and moves to the next line.

```cpp
Serial.println("Arduino");
```

Output:

```text
Arduino
```

---

## 📥 `Serial.read()`

Reads incoming serial data.

```cpp
char data = Serial.read();
```

---

## 👀 `Serial.available()`

Checks if serial data is available.

```cpp
if (Serial.available()) {
}
```

---

# 🧠 5. Decision Structures

## ✅ `if`

```cpp
if (temperature > 30) {
  digitalWrite(13, HIGH);
}
```

---

## ❌ `else`

```cpp
if (button == HIGH) {
  digitalWrite(13, HIGH);
}
else {
  digitalWrite(13, LOW);
}
```

---

## 🔀 `switch-case`

```cpp
switch(value) {

  case 1:
    break;

  case 2:
    break;

  default:
    break;
}
```

Useful when handling multiple conditions.

---

🔁 6. Loops

🔄 `for`

```cpp
for(int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  Serial.println(i);
}
```

### Output

```text
0
1
2
...
9
```

---

## ♾️ `while`

```cpp
while(state == HIGH) {

}
```

Runs while the condition remains true.

---

## 🔂 `do-while`

```cpp
do {

}
while(state == HIGH);
```

Runs at least once.

